segments.text: This is an interview with Dr. R. D. Turk, retired professor of veterinarian parasitology.
Today's date is January 9th, 1980, and this is Terry Anderson.
Right, okay.
This is an interview with Dr. R.D.
Turk, retired professor of veterinarian parasitology.
Today's date is January 9th, 1980, and this is Terry Anderson.
Dr. Turk, could you tell us about your background, where and when you were born?
Well, I was born in a little town of Ice Grove, Missouri.
Population 1,000 on August 1, 1903.
OK. Can you tell us something about your parents?
My parents were Joseph H. and Laura B. Turton.
My dad ran a hardware store in Ice Grove.
And my mother was a housekeeper.
I was number four in a family of six.
Two sisters and three brothers.
What about your father's education?
He had a high school education, but was fairly well read.
And in addition to being a hardware dealer,
He was also mayor several times and president of the local school board.
My mother had two years of college in a local college, which has long now been closed.
Was it a religious college?
No.
What type of people were your parents?
I don't understand what you mean, what kind of people.
Well, could you characterize them for me?
Well, they were just good, hard-working people.
My mother was raised in Babbage, and when she married my dad, she changed over to the Prevotarian place.
He was superintendent of the Prevotarian Sunday School for umpteen years.
We all joined the Presbyterian Church at a comparatively early age.
Can you tell me about your early life, your education?
Well, since we had six kids and ten cows, we had a place on the outskirts of town about 15 acres.
And the cows helped us eat.
and clothes.
Otherwise, I took money from the hardware store.
I repeated the first grade of Astro Community School due to illness.
But then I skipped the fifth grade.
So I graduated from Astro High School in the class of 21, third from the bottom.
The third from the bottom was not due to my lack of ability to learn, but rather to my inability to stay out of mischief.
It's rather difficult to graduate
top man in your class when you've been expelled twice.
Oh, really?
What were you expelled for?
Well, first time for inadvertently hitting a teacher in the head with an eraser.
I wasn't aiming at him.
He had temporarily left the room and I was getting even with the big boy in the front row.
And he returned just in time to see the boy duck and catch the eraser in his eye.
The second time, I and three other seniors decided we would paint Astro HS on the schoolhouse roof with the number 21.
Unfortunately, the principal came in and found the ladder leading up to the attic.
And as he climbed up the steps, I stamped on his toes.
Enough said.
Fortunately, my dad was president of the school board.
So I was returned to school under the proviso that I
make a public apology to all concerned, which, incidentally, was difficult to do.
Following high school, I worked a year in the local post office with the magnificent title of assistant postmaster and the
Yearly stipend of $300.
Yeah.
What year was that?
1922, 300, my goodness.
$25 a month.
Can you tell me about the interest that you had in high school?
Well, I really didn't have too many.
Even that time was
had defective hearing, so I spent most of my time reading Law Comes to Houndo Valley or smoking six guns rather than listening to the lectures.
But I was always interested in animals, partly due to the 10 cows and partly due to being neighbor to a veterinarian.
Since he was a relative newcomer, having arrived there after World War I, he would take me with him to locate the various farms and incidentally to help where help was needed.
I actually made more going with the veterinarian than I did from my job as assistant
Postmaster.
Why did you decide to go on to college?
Well there's a long story about that.
We didn't have too much money so I went to Kansas City, Missouri where I took a job with American Radiator Company.
Radiator Company?
American Radiator Company.
And they offered me a job, $15 a week in the office, or $35 a week in the foundry.
So naturally, I took the foundry job.
I'd saved up $1,500 to go to the bus queue, and the bank closed.
I got 3% back, which you don't have to be a mathematician to realize that was $45.
Was this in 1929 or 30?
No, that was 1923, 24.
And the bank closed them.
Yeah.
The president of the bank had been playing the stock market.
There was one, it was a...
pretty much a one-man bank.
Actually, it was called the Centropolis Bank.
I don't remember the other name, but it was on East 70.
It was on East 64th Street.
American Radiator Company was at 200 East 15th Street, so I banked there as a matter of convenience.
Naturally, I decided to keep my money spent up after that.
So with a new Ford car and lots of help, I had no trouble.
In 1928, the American Radiator Company closed down temporarily.
And at that time, I was a skilled iron moulder.
So I went to Chicago, where I had no trouble
containing a job with the International Harvester Company at 31st and Blue Island in Chicago.
After a year living in Chicago in a 40th boarding house on South Houston Street, I decided in
held it a little bit more for me than being a foundry worker.
So I came back to Kansas City in the spring of 1929.
Spent the remainder of the summer driving an oil truck for the entire oil company.
and enrolled at Kansas State, which at that time, Kansas State Agriculture College, KSAC, in Budner Medicine.
While in the foundry,
I also moonlighted somewhat driving taxi cab a few months one winter when I was laid off and boxing at the Bell Telephone Company Friday night smokers.
Really?
I was a pretty good boxer at 127 pounds, but one night I met a Mexican boy with six hands.
I didn't remember anything from Friday afternoon, or Friday evening rather, till Monday morning, so I decided that boxing was not for me.
The only nice thing was when I went to Kansas State
I didn't have to take physical education because I'd been a professional athlete.
Did you ever make much money boxing?
Oh, yes.
$25 a night.
Oh, is that what it was?
$25 a night?
For three three-round bouts.
Three three-round?
With three different opponents?
Well, no.
One round went three three-round bouts.
Oh, I see.
Oh, they had a whole bunch of hungry kids.
Get up there and flail around and get your ass knocked over.
Yeah, all right.
I had a little difficulty getting into Kansas State for several reasons.
First, I was eight years older than
the majority of my class since I graduated from Ash Grove High School in 1921 and entered college in 1929.
Second, I'd had no physics, no chemistry, and only three units of English.
However, I took a comprehensive examination
and past with satisfactory results due primarily to my omnipotent reading.
I was born slightly deaf, or rather with impaired hearing.
So reading was really my pastime.
Much to my surprise,
I ended up my freshman year with a straight A average with the exception of military.
When they'd holler the command, I would usually step behind because I couldn't hear very good.
I went back to the
and got accused for military, so one year in the ROTC as a freshman is all the military record I had.
I graduated from Kansas State with the highest grades in veterinary medicine
that had been turned in up to that time.
I think it's been surpassed since then.
But anyway, with the exception of military science, the only other B grade I made was in poultry husbandry.
Due to the fact I
used to return to Kansas City on occasional weekends, and sometimes would miss the train coming back, and thus miss the 8 o'clock Monday morning session in Poultry Husbandry.
Well, could you describe the curriculum at Kansas State?
Well, let me tell you first how I stayed in there.
Oh, fine.
I got a job in the department of pathology and so I could work from seven to eight and from after school till as long as was necessary.
I got 25 cents an hour my freshman year and then
In my sophomore year, I was zoomed up to 35 minutes an hour, which, with a little help from home, let me keep body and soul together.
The curriculum, incidentally, the job was mine after
school hours I was there by myself with the job of cleaning up glassware and the microscopes and various other duties.
So I spent quite a bit of time studying on company time.
Nevertheless, it must have been difficult during the Depression.
It must have been difficult during the Depression.
It was.
It was rather difficult, but it had its advantages.
Two hamburgers were a nickel.
Mm-hmm.
All soft drinks were a nickel.
Pie was 10 cents a quarter.
And it took a lot of ingenuity to spend a dollar for one meal.
Mm-hmm.
I joined Masonic Lodge in March of 1929.
So I joined the Acacia Fraternity in 1931 and was president of the fraternity the year I graduated.
The curriculum was primarily basic.
The freshman year was anatomy, histology, and chemistry.
And I forget the other sophomore year,
pathology, more anatomy, biological chemistry, elementary course in physics, and so forth.
Junior and senior years we got into clinics.
And really, I don't remember the names of the specific courses, but we had non-infectious diseases, infectious diseases, clinical diagnosis, and more pathology.
Due to my job in the pathology department, most of the pathology was just a review.
And I graduated with honors.
Since the world was not meeting a path to my door in 1933, I stayed on in the Department of Pathology as an assistant until September 1 at the magnificent salary of 75 cents an hour.
I then took a job with the University of Illinois at $1,500 a year.
But due to my defective hearing,
I had a little difficulty, and so I quit.
What were you teaching at the University of Illinois?
I wasn't teaching.
I was clinical assistant.
I see.
And came back to Columbus, Kansas.
and open to practice.
That was a mistake.
By Christmas 1933, I, pardon me, no, I netted $200 cash.
In May of 1934,
It stopped raining, and the grasshoppers moved in.
And in August 1934, I netted $60.
Since my fixed expenses were $5 a month for our office,
and $10 a week for board and room with gasoline, $0.15 a gallon, I wasn't breaking even.
About that time, the federal government instituted what is known as the cattle reduction program.

The idea was to, rather than plow the little pigs under, or rather plow the cotton under and kill all the pigs, that they would test the cattle and take out the diseased ones and leave the healthy cattle there.
So I went to Oklahoma.
Pardon me.
So I went to Oklahoma working for USDA.
At the French's salary of $1,500 a year, plus a nickel a mile on my car, plus $5 a day, which included hotel board, hotel room, and meals.
That must have been considered a very good job.
It was a good job.
It was cash.
But I am ashamed to admit it, but I cheated sometimes on the meals.
I'd jack up the back wheel of the car and let it run while I was eating dinner.
Five cents a mile for seven miles would give you 35 cents, which
quite a feat.
Then in 1935, due to my academic background, they decided to move me into Oklahoma City to take charge of the Bang Disease Laboratory.
The what disease?
B-A-N-G.
Possibly S. More commonly known as
brucellosis, which is an infectious abortion of cattle.
We prepared our own antigen and tested all the samples brought in from other young men who were also working for the
Among the employees was a young lady named June Hardesty, H-A-R-D-E-S-Y, who was a skilled laboratory technician.
She worked for me a year.
And I've been working for her ever since.

To make a long story short, in December of 1935, I was told by the power to be that I was to be transferred to Baltimore, Maryland for the United States Department of Agriculture to work in a laboratory there.
I didn't like the East.
I'd been to Chicago.
So I was really lost what to do.
I wanted to get married, and I didn't want to go back where the snow flies.
So out of the clear blue sky, I got a letter from Dr. H. Smith.
It was a Texas ag culture experiment statement.
asking me would I be interested in a job at Texas A&M.
He didn't say what the job consisted of or what the salary paid or anything.
How did he even know of you?
Had he met you before?
He had written around.
Oh, he had written around.
I imagine.
I never did find out.
I never did find out.
And he just grinned and said, well, I just heard of you.
But anyway.
I was offered a job at $2,400 a year at Texas A&M.
That's $200 on 12 months.
And most of the employees of the college proper, a lot of them were getting $1,500 and $1,800 for nine months.
In fact, there were PhDs in chemistry and physics and English and various
liberal arts that were only getting 15, 18, or $2,000 for nine months.
So I tickled the old man, I think, or rather the word would be amused.
I just wrote back, yes, when will I report?
And that tickled him, so he said February 1.
That was all the correspondence we went through for my job.
But I wanted the laboratory because of my hearing
So June and I got married February 18th.
I spent a week at home visiting and reported to Texas on February 1, 1936.
June wondered what kind of a town was College Station.
I said, I don't know.
I have no idea.
So we came through Curtin, and I said, well, it's not very big, is it?
Then we saw another town that said Bryan.
I said, well, I think College of Dayton is fairly close to Bryan.
So we came into Bryan, stayed at the old LaSalle Hotel.
I went out the next morning to report.
And much to my surprise, College of Dayton was just a campus.
All the profs lived on the campus and everybody else over there.
There were a few colored people living outside and there were some farms come up almost against it.
Dr. Smith said, well, I'm glad you're here.
I said, I'm glad I'm here also.
So I wanted to be honest with him and I told him, I said, I don't hear very well.
He said, well, that's all right.
Don't worry about that.
I'll talk loud enough you can hear me.
